               <note resp="#msb, #st">The nine muses in Greco-Roman myth are the daughters of Zeus and Mnemosyne who serve as patronesses of the arts. They are Calliope (epic poetry), Clio (history), Euterpe (flutes and lyric poetry), Thalia (comedy and pastoral poetry), Melpomene (tragedy), Terpsichore (dance), Erato (love poetry), Polyhymnia (sacred poetry), Urania (astronomy), and they inhabit the mythical Mt. Parnassus. The word muse can also designate an artist's inspiration for their pieces whether it be a painting, a sculpture or some other form of an art. Women writers are sometimes (condescendingly) referred to as the "tenth muse."</note>
